                <head>125. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At a meeting of the National Security Council on February 24, Admiral <persName
                        corresp="#p_RAAW1">Radford</persName> stated that “at four o’clock this
                    morning the Chinese Nationalists had begun to evacuate their forces from
                    Nanchi-San <pb facs="0331" n="303" xml:id="pg_303"/> [<hi rend="italic">Nan-chi
                        Shan</hi>]. For once he was able to inform the members of the Council of
                    such information before they read it in the press or learned it over the radio.
                    The United States had informed the Chinese Nationalists that it would not assist
                    them in holding Nanchi-San, and in response to this statement they had begun the
                    evacuation.” (Memorandum of discussion by <persName corresp="#p_GSE1"
                        >Gleason</persName>; <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>
                    Library, Whitman File, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Records)</p>
                <p>Telegram 584 from Taipei, February 25, stated that the evacuation of both
                    civilians and military personnel from Nanchi had been completed that morning.
                    (Department of State, Central Files, 793.5/2–2555)</p>
            </div>
